A declaration against Prince Rupert, or, An argument, whereby it appears, that Prince Rupert, and all that joyne with him in this unnaturall war against the Parliament, are guilty of high-treason, with an exposition of the stat. of II. Hen. 7. whereby it appeares, that those who follow the advice and imployment of the Parliament, are freed from treason, or any other offence concerning their particular actions in that service. By P.B. gent. P. B., Gent.
8 p.
[s.n.], London : Printed in the yeare 1642. [i.e. 1643]
Variant: title page lacks "By P.B. Gent."; line 3 of title ends "Rupert:". Annotation on Thomason copy: "Jan: 19". Reproduction of the original in the British Library.
